In TypeScript, you can use type annotations to specify the type of a value, and you can also use type aliases to define a type alias for a specific value. Here's how you can achieve this:

### Using Type Annotations
Type annotations are a powerful way to specify the type of a value. You can use them to indicate that a value may have multiple types but in practice, it will only have one.

```typescript
let value: number | string | null;

// This will be a number
value = 42;

// This will be a string
value = "hello";

// This will be null
value = null;
```

### Using Type Aliases
Type aliases can be used to define a type alias for a specific value. This can be useful when you want to indicate that a value may have multiple types but in practice, it will only have one.

```typescript
let value: number | string | null;

// This will be a number
value = 42;

// This will be a string
